{"key":"post-8730883","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8730883</id>\n<content>One of the biggest causes of bacterial contamination is the exhaled breath of the cultivator, and to a lesser degree, bacteria from under the fingernails and other skin cells that shed during the process.&amp;nbsp; That's why it's important to use a glovebox or flowhood, and as added protection, wear a surgical mask.&amp;nbsp; I usually work in front of a laminar flow hood, wear latex gloves and surgical mask(not dust mask) and a hair net.&amp;nbsp; In addition, flame sterilize until red hot before each jar, and then let a drop or two of solution spill out to cool the needle slightly just before injecting while it's still hot.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's amazing how few contaminated syringes I buy when using that method. &lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/grin.gif&quot; alt=&quot;:grin:&quot; title=&quot;:grin:&quot;/&gt;&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8730987</next>\n<prev>8730169</prev>\n<first>8721250</first>\n<last>8731422</last>\n<when>1217987927</when>\n<utime>08/06/08 04:58 AM</utime>\n</post>"}